[[ja:弟橘媛]] '''Ototachibana-hime''' (弟橘媛) was the wife of {{ill|Yamato Takeru|ja|ヤマトタケル}}, according to the {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀}}. In the {{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記}}, she is referred to as Otachibana-hime no Mikoto (弟橘比売命), the consort of Yamato Takeru.
== Ototachibana-hime in the Kojiki and Nihon Shoki == In the {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀}}, she is described as the daughter of {{ill|Oshiyama-no-Sukune|ja|忍山宿禰}}, an ancestor of the {{ill|Hozumi clan|ja|穂積氏}}. She bore Yamato Takeru a son, {{ill|Wakatakehiko-no-Mikoto|ja|稚武彦王}}.<ref>宇治谷孟 『日本書紀（上）全現代語訳』 174ページ</ref>
{{Quotation|While crossing the sea from Sagami to Kazusa, Yamato Takeru boasted, “This small sea, I could leap over it.” However, a violent storm arose, and the ship began to drift. Ototachibana-hime, his consort, said, “This storm must be the work of the sea god. Allow me to enter the sea as your substitute.” With these words, she entered the waves, and the storm ceased. The ship safely reached the shore, and the sea was named Tachibana Sea in her honor.<ref>宇治谷孟 『日本書紀（上）全現代語訳』 168ページ</ref>}}
In {{ill|Mobara, Chiba|ja|茂原市}}, {{ill|Tachibana Shrine (Mobara)|ja|橘樹神社}} honors Ototachibana-hime. The shrine is an {{ill|Engishiki|ja|延喜式}}-listed shrine, one of Kazusa's five major shrines, and the only shrine recorded in historical texts to enshrine her. According to legend, Yamato Takeru planted a tachibana tree as her grave marker here.<ref>菊池利夫 『東京湾史』 80ページ</ref>
In the {{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記}}, Ototachibana-hime offered herself to calm the sea gods’ wrath as Yamato Takeru encountered a storm at Hashirimizu. She placed eight layers of sedge, hide, and silk mats on the waves, sat on them, and entered the sea, calming the waters.<ref>次田真幸 『古事記（中）全訳注』 150ページ</ref>
{{Quotation|She said, “I shall enter the sea as your substitute. Please proceed safely with your campaign.” She then spread eight layers of sedge, hide, and silk mats over the waves, seated herself on them, and entered the sea. The storm subsided, and the ship advanced. As she descended, she sang:<br> * “In Aibu’s fields, flames rise; standing amid them, you questioned me, my lord.”<br> Her comb was found washed ashore seven days later, and Yamato Takeru enshrined it, creating her tomb.<ref>次田真幸 『古事記（中）全訳注』 147ページ</ref>}}
The comb is said to be enshrined at Tachibana Shrine, and her poem expresses her gratitude to Yamato Takeru for his care during a previous ordeal. Yamato Takeru’s lament, “Azuma haya” (“My wife!”), upon reaching Azuma, is said to have named the eastern provinces “Azuma,” a geonymic tale.<ref>宇治谷孟 『日本書紀（上）全現代語訳』 169ページ</ref><ref>次田真幸 『古事記（中）全訳注』 153ページ</ref>
== Hitachi no Kuni Fudoki == In the {{ill|Hitachi no Kuni Fudoki|ja|常陸国風土記}}, Ototachibana-hime appears as Ōtachibana-hime or Empress Tachibana, while Yamato Takeru is referred to as Emperor Yamato.<ref>植垣節也 『風土記 新編日本古典文学全集5』 388ページ</ref>
== Sendaikujihongi == In the {{ill|Sendaikujihongi|ja|先代旧事本紀}}, Ototachibana-hime is recorded as the mother of Wakatakehiko-no-Mikoto and eight other sons.<ref>植垣節也 『風土記 新編日本古典文学全集5』 417ページ</ref>
== Shrines and Legends == Ototachibana-hime’s legend is central to shrines across Kazusa (modern-day Chiba) and beyond. Shrines such as {{ill|Tachibana Shrine (Kanagawa)|ja|橘樹神社}}, {{ill|Nomura Shrine|ja|能褒野神社}}, and {{ill|Hashirimizu Shrine|ja|走水神社 (横須賀市)}} enshrine her alongside Yamato Takeru.
Places like {{ill|Sodegaura|ja|袖ケ浦}} are named after the legend of her sleeves washing ashore. The sacred tachibana tree associated with her suggests she may have been a shaman.<ref>小野一之・鈴木彰・谷口榮・樋口州男 『人物伝小辞典 古代・中世編』 54ページ</ref>
